BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Poetry of Cinema: a workshop
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260803T093000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260803T150000
DTSTAMP:20260723T114709Z
UID:dartmouth-82082@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=82082\n\nDescription:\nIn this workshop\, we'll explore the creat
 ive crossroads between poetry and cinema\, and learn how poets and filmmak
 ers use image\, language\, and memory to create emotionally resonant work.
  Drawing on poems\, screenplay excerpts\, and film clips\, we'll examine h
 ow a single lyric image can become the foundation for character\, scene\, 
 and narrative\, with a special focus on crafting the opening pages of a sc
 reenplay. Whether you're interested in writing poetry\, screenplays\, or b
 oth\, you'll leave with practical strategies for getting started\, shaping
  your first pages\, and approaching revision with fresh eyes.\nSCHEDULE\n9
 :30-10:30 AM - John Wall Barger:\nExploring Tarkovsky’s 1966 Soviet-Russ
 ian film Andrei Rublev\, and poems by Marie Howe\, to show how a film is l
 ike a poem\, and how watching great films can inspire us to write poems.\n
 11:00 AM-12:00 PM - Elena Karina Byrne:\nPoetry's Cinematic Propositions\;
  how poetry and film share key elements of discovery\, utilizing the trans
 formative ingredients of language\, action\, and image.\n12:00-1:30 PM - L
 unch provided.\n1:30-3:00 PM - Perry Janes:\nHow the lyric image crosses f
 rom poetry to film\, and how that can serve as an originating point for yo
 ur screenplay\nJohn Wall Barger\nis the author of seven books of poems and
  a collection of essays. His latest book of poems\, Resurrection Pie\, jus
 t came out with LSU Press. He’s a contract editor for Frontenac House\, 
 lives in Vermont\, and lectures in the Writing Program at Dartmouth Colleg
 e.\nElena Karina Byrne\nis a screenwriter\, essayist\, reviewer\, multi-me
 dia artist\, and editor. She also works as a freelance lecturer and nation
 al arts programs curator. Author of five collections of poetry including I
 f This Makes You Nervous (Omnidawn)\, No\, Don’t (What Books Press)\, Sq
 uander (Omnidawn)\, MASQUE (Tupelo Press)\, and The Flammable Bird (Zoo Pr
 ess/Tupelo Press)\, Elena is a Pushcart Prize and Best American Poetry rec
 ipient. Her poems\, reviews\, essays\, and interviews can be found in POET
 RY\, The Kenyon Review\, The Paris Review\, Poetry International\, Poetry 
 Daily\, Ploughshares\, BOMB\, Academy of American Poets Poem-A-Day\, and e
 lsewhere.\nPerry Janes\nis the author of the poetry collection FIND ME WHE
 N YOU’RE READY (Curbstone Books/Northwestern University Press\, 2024)\, 
 winner of the Eric Hoffer Award for Poetry. A recipient of the Pushcart Pr
 ize\, his poems and short stories have appeared in POETRY\, Electric Liter
 ature\, Poem-a-Day\, Best New Poets\, The Threepenny Review\, Zyzzyva\, Th
 e Michigan Quarterly Review\, Subtropics\, Prairie Schooner\, Beloit Poetr
 y Journal\, The Adroit Journal\, The Missouri Review\, and others. He earn
 ed his MFA in Poetry from Warren Wilson College\, and his BA from the Univ
 ersity of Michigan\, Ann Arbor\, where he was a 5-time recipient of the Ho
 pwood Award.\nVievee Francis\nis the author of five books of poetry: Blue-
 Tail Fly (2007)\, Horse in the Dark (2010)\, Forest Primeval (2016)\, The 
 Shared World (2023)\, and the forthcoming Cleaning the Houses of the Dead.
  Born in West Texas and raised in Metropolitan Detroit\, Francis has recei
 ved numerous awards and recognition for her work including a Guggenheim Fe
 llowship (2024)\, a Vermont Book Award (2023)\, the Aiken Taylor Award for
  Modern American Poetry (2021)\, the Kingsley Tufts Poetry Award (2017)\, 
 and the Hurston Wright Legacy Award (2016). Francis\, along with composer 
 Jonathan Berger and artist Enrico Riley\, wrote the libretto for the trans
 disciplinary opera The Ritual of Breath which premiered in 2022. She has s
 erved as an Associate Editor for Callaloo and currently holds the Burlingt
 on Northern Foundation Professorship in Creative Writing at Dartmouth Coll
 ege.\n\nSponsor / organizer: Literary Arts Bridge\n\nAudience: Public\n\nS
 ource: Dartmouth\n\nWhy this was included: explicit food-service wording\;
  food keyword near service context\n\nFood availability is inferred from t
 he source listing\; verify details before attending.
LOCATION:Literary Arts Bridge (7 Lebanon St. Suite 105)
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://home.dartmouth.edu/events/event?event=82082
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Publishing Talk: Catherine Tudish & Peter Orner
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260805T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260805T190000
DTSTAMP:20260723T114709Z
UID:dartmouth-82084@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=82084\n\nDescription:\nBorn into an air force family\,\nCatherine
  Tudish\ngrew up moving from one place to the next\, living in England and
  France\, as well as both coasts and the heartland of America. After recei
 ving a B.A. in English from Southern Illinois University and a Ph.D. in Am
 erican Studies from St. Louis University\, she began work as a teacher and
  journalist. Her first book\, a collection of stories called\nTenney’s L
 anding\n\, was published by Scribner in 2005. Since then\, she has publish
 ed the novel\nAmerican Cream\,\nas well as numerous articles and essays in
  regional newspapers and magazines. Her latest book\,\nA Thousand Souls: A
  Novel\nin Stories\,\nwill be published by Acre Books in April 2026. Cathe
 rine has taught writing and literature at George Washington University\, H
 arvard\, Dartmouth\, and the Bread Loaf School of English. She lives in a 
 village in central Vermont and teaches a community writing workshop at the
  local library.\nBorn in Chicago\,\nPeter Orner\nis the author of eight ac
 claimed books\, including\nThe Gossip Columnist's Daughter\n\;\nMaggie Bro
 wn & Others\; Love and Shame and Love\; Esther Stories\n\, finalist for th
 e PEN/Hemingway Award\; and\nAm I Alone Here?\n\, a finalist for the Natio
 nal Book Critics Circle Award. His work has appeared in\nThe New Yorker\, 
 the Paris Review\, The Believer\,\nand\nThe Best American Short Stories\n\
 , and received four Pushcart Prizes. A former Guggenheim fellow and recipi
 ent of the Rome Prize from the American Academy of Arts and Letters\, Orne
 r is professor of Creative Writing at Dartmouth College. He lives with his
  family in Vermont\, where he's also a volunteer firefighter.\n\nSponsor /
  organizer: Literary Arts Bridge\n\nAudience: Public\n\nSource: Dartmouth\
 n\nWhy this was included: Free Food category\; explicit food-service wordi
 ng\; food or meal keyword in title/summary\n\nFood availability is inferre
 d from the source listing\; verify details before attending.
LOCATION:Literary Arts Bridge (7 Lebanon St. Suite 105)
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://home.dartmouth.edu/events/event?event=82084
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Xpressions of Dartmouth 2026
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260807T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260807T170000
DTSTAMP:20260723T114709Z
UID:dartmouth-groups-1630869@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://dartmouthgroups.dartmouth.edu
 /rsvp_boot?id=1630869\n\nDescription:\nSummer term often boasts fun and gr
 eat weather\, yet with limited upbeat spaces we have during other terms. I
 n collaboration with campus and community partners\, Xpressions of Dartmou
 th aims to offer engaging programming during the summer term\, providing o
 pportunities for the entire Dartmouth community to connect and explore dif
 ferent forms of expression\, from engaging in the fine arts and nature\, o
 r traveling and exploring a new city and tasting foods from a variety of c
 ultural backgrounds.\nWe are excited to bring back Xpressions of Dartmouth
  with a mix of new and returning events. We hope you join us for our FINAL
  event of the summer\, Xpressions of Dartmouth: An Exhibition of Expressio
 ns. We invite all members of the Dartmouth community to explore forms of e
 xpression complete with local food trucks (Making the CuTx\, —\, — and
  Sisters of Anarchy)\, lawn games\, activities\, raffles/giveaways\, Kona 
 Ice\, a live DJ\, and your favorite offices and organizations!\nFind us on
  Mass Row from 2-5pm on Friday\, August 7th!\n\nSponsor / organizer: Offic
 e of Pluralism and Leadership\n\nSource: Dartmouth Groups\n\nWhy this was 
 included: food or meal keyword in title/summary\n\nFood availability is in
 ferred from the source listing\; verify details before attending.
LOCATION:Private Location (sign in to display)
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://dartmouthgroups.dartmouth.edu/rsvp_boot?id=1630869
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Pizza Retreat
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260808T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260808T180000
DTSTAMP:20260723T114709Z
UID:dartmouth-81981@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=81981\nhttps://cglink.me/2ob/r1630490\nhttps://dartmouthgroups.da
 rtmouth.edu/rsvp_boot?id=1630490\n\nDescription:\nEver been on a mindfulne
 ss retreat centered around pizza? Neither have we.\nThat’s why we’re e
 xcited to bring you Pizza Retreat! Come to the O-Farm on August 8th for a 
 one-of-a-kind experience. We'll be slowing down\, savoring the simple plea
 sures of summer\, offering mindful movement and plenty of space to make th
 e day your own. Oh\, and of course-- pizza making and eating!\nIf you want
  to create a deeper appreciation for where food comes from\, partake in me
 aningful conversations\, or simply enjoy chill time outdoors\, then Pizza 
